Nathan Wolfson wrote:
> 
> This means:
> 
> People submitting lists to be can do it exactly as they have been EXCEPT
> absolute line breaks (that is, at the end of a field, like at the end of all
> the songs in SETI or at the end of the RECORDINGS list), there needs to be
> some 7-bit character that we are not already using in the setlists.  This
> character will be appended by me for posting lists to the WEB (with <br>,
> for those who are interested) and this character will be used by the search
> engine(s) to know that one field has ended and another has begun.

Nathan,
Could you open the setlists in a text editor, and do a find/replace_all like:

Find "SET1" and replace it with "<br>Set1"?

before posting the setlists to the Web? You could even do a replace of 
"<br><br><br>Band" for the first field, so that you wouldn't have to worry 
about the blank space between shows. HTML doesn't care whether the break comes 
at the end or beginning of a field (they both display the same way), and this 
way people wouldn't have to add a plus sign at the end of each field. Is this 
what you had in mind, or am I missing something?
